4.7.  Time Trust Anchor Mechanism

   To mitigate risks from single time source failures or NTP
   deviations, JEP implementations MAY implement a Time Trust Anchor
   (TTA) mechanism using multiple independent time sources.

4.7.1.  Time Source Configuration

   TTA-enabled implementations MUST configure at least two of the
   following time sources:

   - Local NTP with authenticated NTS (Network Time Security)
   - SCITT transparency service timestamp (if SCITT usage
     enabled, see Section 5.2)
   - Hardware-backed trusted clock (e.g., TPM RTC, TEE secure
     clock, or hardware security module clock)

4.7.2.  Time Consensus Algorithm

   When multiple time sources are configured, implementations MUST
   apply the following consensus algorithm:

   1. Collect timestamps from all available sources
   2. Discard outliers exceeding 2x the configured tolerance window
   3. Select the median timestamp as authoritative
   4. If sources disagree beyond tolerance window, enter
      SUSPECTED state and trigger manual review

4.7.3.  Dynamic Tolerance Adjustment

   Implementations MAY support dynamic tolerance window adjustment
   based on historical time source stability:

   - Baseline window: 5 seconds (as specified in Section 3.7)
   - Minimum window: 1 second (for high-stability environments)
   - Maximum window: 30 seconds (for degraded network conditions)

   Window adjustments MUST be logged in Tier 2 contextual evidence
   for audit traceability.


5.  Extensions and Integration

5.1.  Extension Mechanism

   JEP supports protocol extensions through IANA registration.
   Extensions MUST NOT violate core protocol semantics.

5.2.  SCITT Usage

   SCITT [draft-ietf-scitt-architecture] may provide timestamp
   services for JEP receipts. This is optional; JEP verification
   does not require SCITT integration.

5.3.  RATS Usage

   RATS [RFC9334] attestations may be recorded in Tier 2 contextual
   evidence. This is optional.

5.3.1.  TEE Evidence Encoding in Tier 2

   When TEE environment evidence is included in Tier 2
   contextual_evidence, it MUST be encoded according to the Entity
   Attestation Token (EAT) format [RFC9711] or as raw measurements
   following the encoding specified below.

   EAT-based encoding (RECOMMENDED):
   - Use EAT as defined in RFC 9711
   - Include eat_nonce for freshness
   - Include oemid and hwversion for device identification
   - Include measurements in manifests claim or dedicated
     measurement claims

   Raw measurement encoding (for constrained environments):
   - tee_type: String identifying TEE type ("Intel-TDX",
     "AMD-SEV-SNP", "ARM-CCA", "TPM2")
   - measurement_values: Object containing TEE-specific measurements

5.3.2.  TEE-Specific Measurement Formats

   Intel TDX:
   - mr_td: 48-byte measurement of guest firmware image (hex
     encoded string)
   - rtmrs: Array of 4 runtime measurement registers, each 48-byte
     hex encoded
   - tee_tcb_svn: 16-byte security version number (hex encoded)
   - report_data: 64-byte user data or nonce (hex encoded)

   AMD SEV-SNP:
   - measurement: 48-byte launch measurement (hex encoded)
   - report_id: 32-byte unique report identifier (hex encoded)
   - report_id_ma: 32-byte migration agent report ID (hex encoded)
   - reported_tcb: 8-byte reported TCB version (hex encoded)
   - chip_id: 64-byte unique chip identifier (hex encoded)

   ARM CCA:
   - realm_initial_measurement: 32-byte realm initial measurement
   - rim_extend_count: Integer, extension count
   - personalization_value: 64-byte personalization value

   TPM2:
   - pcr_values: Object mapping PCR index (0-23) to SHA-256 hash
   - quote_signature: Base64-encoded TPM quote signature
   - ak_cert: Attestation Key certificate (PEM format)

5.3.3.  TEE Binding Verification Procedure

   When verifying TEE evidence in Tier 2, implementations MUST:

   1. Verify EAT signature or TPM quote signature using known
      public keys or endorsement certificates
   2. Verify eat_nonce or report_data matches the receipt's
      jep_rid (receipt ID) to prevent replay attacks
   3. Verify measurements against reference values from
      manufacturer or deployment-specific policy
   4. Verify TEE security version numbers meet minimum
      requirements configured for the use case

