   while retaining Tier 1/2 evidence proving "compliance erasure
   obligation fulfilled."  This design references ENISA "Data
   Protection Engineering" recommendations on "achieving data
   protection principles through advanced cryptographic techniques."

7.5.2.  EU AI Act Compliance Mapping

   For high-risk AI system transparency obligations effective
   August 2, 2026:

   - AI Agent Collaboration Accountability: $Delegate primitive
     (4.1.2) supports multi-AI agent responsibility tracing,
     satisfying AI Act Article 12 "traceability" requirements

   - Bias Detection Sensitive Data Processing: Three-tier
     architecture ensures sensitive judgment content only stored as
     hash (Tier 3), auditors only access metadata (Tier 2),
     compliant with EDPB guidelines on data minimization and privacy
     by design

   - Synthetic Content Marking: JEP responsibility chain can serve
     as infrastructure for deepfake accountability (requires
     coordination with content watermarking technology)

   - Human Oversight Record: AI Act extension (G.5.4) supports
     recording human supervisor ID and conformity assessment
     identifiers

7.5.3.  Judicial Recognition of Cryptographic Erasure

   The cryptographic erasure mechanism (7.3) through "logical
   tombstone" design, while destroying decryption keys, retains:

   - Tier 1: Public agent ID (rotatable) - proves "who"
   - Tier 2: Authorization chain and timestamp (encrypted) - proves
     "when, based on what authorization"
   - PKD (Proof of Key Destruction) - proves "compliant deletion"

   This design references ENISA "Data Protection Engineering" report
   technical recommendations on "encryption techniques for deletion
   rights" and EDPB "Right to be Forgotten Guidelines" on technical
   measure sufficiency standards.  EDPB has listed "right to erasure"
   as 2025 priority enforcement theme, and JEP's cryptographic
   erasure mechanism provides organizations with verifiable
   compliance tools.

   This design is intended to support compliance demonstration
   with erasure obligations, though final recognition depends on
   specific jurisdictional interpretation and regulatory guidance.

