Appendix E.  Implementation Guide

E.1.  Reference Implementation

   Reference Implementation v1.0 is available at:
   https://github.com/hjs-spec/jep-reference-impl

   Implementation details:
   - Language: Rust 1.75 with ring cryptography crate
   - License: Apache-2.0
   - Test coverage: 94% line coverage, 100% state machine coverage

E.2.  Minimal Viable Implementation (Pseudocode)

   ```python
   class Receipt:
       def __init__(self, event_id, actor, decision_hash):
           self.event_id = event_id
           self.actor = actor
           self.decision_hash = decision_hash
           self.prev_hash = None
           self.signature = None

       def sign(self, private_key):
           data = self.canonicalize()
           self.signature = sign(private_key, data)

       def verify(self, public_key):
           data = self.canonicalize()
           return verify(public_key, data, self.signature)

       def canonicalize(self):
           # Use JCS (RFC 8785)
           return jcs(self.to_dict())
   ```

E.3.  Implementation Checklist

   - [ ] All four primitives implemented
   - [ ] State machine (7 states) supported
   - [ ] Three verification modes (open/platform/dual)
   - [ ] Chain depth limit (10 levels)
   - [ ] Dual-contract enforcement
   - [ ] Cryptographic erasure (optional)
   - [ ] TEE binding (optional)
   - [ ] IANA registry usage

E.4.  Common Implementation Errors

   - Forgetting JCS canonicalization causing signature verification
     failure
   - Not using UTC for timestamps causing cross-timezone issues
   - Not checking chain depth causing DoS vulnerability
   - Wrong signature verification order (SHOULD verify prev_hash
     first)
   - Not handling DELEGATING timeout rollback

E.5.  Performance Optimization

   - Cache frequently used public key verification results
   - Parallel verification of multi-level delegation chains
   - Use CBOR compact format to reduce bandwidth
   - Pre-compute hash values


