Appendix G.  Protocol Extensions

   This appendix defines optional extensions to the core JEP
   protocol.  Extensions are organized by priority level based on
   implementation recommendations.

G.1.  Extension Mechanism Principles

   The following principles govern all JEP extensions:

   1. Extensions MUST NOT modify core protocol semantics (four
      primitives, three modes, three-tier architecture)
   2. Extensions MUST be registered via IANA (Section 8.4)
   3. Extensions SHOULD follow reverse domain naming (e.g.,
      org.example.jep.extension)
   4. Extensions MAY declare compatibility levels (full|wire|none)
      as defined in Section 5.5.1

G.2.  Priority 1 Extensions (Strongly Recommended)

   The following extensions are strongly recommended for production
   deployments to ensure interoperability, reliability, and
   recoverability.

G.2.1.  TEE Evidence Format

   Purpose: Standardize TEE evidence encoding in Tier 2
   contextual_evidence for cross-platform interoperability.

   Extension Identifier: org.ietf.jep.ext.tee-evidence

   Compatibility: wire

   Specification:
   - tee_type: REQUIRED.  String identifying TEE type.  Values:
     "Intel-TDX", "AMD-SEV-SNP", "ARM-CCA", "TPM2"
   - format: REQUIRED.  String.  Values: "eat", "raw"
   - evidence: REQUIRED.  Base64-encoded attestation evidence
   - verifier: OPTIONAL.  URI of external verification service
   - timestamp: REQUIRED.  Unix timestamp of attestation generation

   Example:
   ```json
   {
     "contextual_evidence": {
       "tee_type": "Intel-TDX",
       "format": "eat",
       "evidence": "base64-encoded-EAT...",
       "verifier": "https://verify.example/intel-tdx",
       "timestamp": 1712345678
     }
   }
   ```

   Verification: See Section 5.3.3 for detailed verification
   procedure.

G.2.2.  Resolution Event ($Resolve)

   Purpose: Provide automated recovery from DISPUTED state through
   authorized governance intervention.

   Extension Identifier: org.ietf.jep.ext.resolution

   Compatibility: full

   Specification:
   - Adds new primitive: $Resolve
   - Adds new states: DISPUTED_FROZEN, RESOLVED_CONTINUE,
     RESOLVED_INVALID
   - Adds new error code: RESOLUTION_REQUIRED

   Resolution Event Format:
   ```json
   {
     "primitive": {
       "type": "RESOLVE",
       "payload": {
         "disputed_receipt": "uuid-of-disputed-receipt",
         "resolution": "RESOLVED_CONTINUE|RESOLVED_INVALID|RESOLVED_REPLACE",
         "resolution_proof": "multi-signature-from-governance",
         "new_anchor": "uuid-of-new-anchor-receipt",
         "effective_from": 1712345678,
         "resolution_statement": "Human-readable explanation"
       }
     }
   }
   ```

   State Transitions:
   - ACTIVE/DELEGATED -> DISPUTED_FROZEN (on dual mode conflict)
   - DISPUTED_FROZEN -> RESOLVED_CONTINUE (chain continues)
   - DISPUTED_FROZEN -> RESOLVED_INVALID (chain re-initiated)

   See Section 4.5.5 for detailed recovery procedure.

G.2.3.  Multi-Source Time Validation

   Purpose: Enhance time reliability through multiple independent
   time sources with consensus algorithm.

   Extension Identifier: org.ietf.jep.ext.multi-time

   Compatibility: full

   Specification:
   - timestamp_validation.mode: REQUIRED.  String.  Values:
     "strict", "tolerant", "multi_source"
   - timestamp_validation.sources: REQUIRED when mode is
     "multi_source".  Array of time source objects.
   - timestamp_validation.consensus: REQUIRED when mode is
     "multi_source".  String.  Values: "majority", "median",
     "min_drift"

   Time Source Object:
   - type: REQUIRED.  String.  Values: "local_ntp",
     "scitt_anchor", "hardware_clock"
   - offset_ms: REQUIRED for local_ntp.  Integer.
   - timestamp: REQUIRED for scitt_anchor.  Integer.
   - tolerance_ms: REQUIRED for scitt_anchor.  Integer.
   - evidence: REQUIRED for hardware_clock.  Base64.

   Example:
   ```json
   {
     "timestamp_validation": {
       "mode": "multi_source",
       "sources": [
         {"type": "local_ntp", "offset_ms": 50},
         {"type": "scitt_anchor", "timestamp": 1712345678,
          "tolerance_ms": 5000},
         {"type": "hardware_clock", "evidence": "base64..."}
       ],
       "consensus": "median"
     }
   }
   ```

   Consensus Algorithm: See Section 4.7.2.

